### 5. DB backup/restore depends on host binaries and TLS behavior
- Severity: Medium
- Evidence: [apps/web/src/app/[locale]/admin/db-actions.ts:94-129](/Users/hletrd/flash-shared/gallery/apps/web/src/app/%5Blocale%5D/admin/db-actions.ts#L94-L129), [apps/web/src/app/[locale]/admin/db-actions.ts:232-341](/Users/hletrd/flash-shared/gallery/apps/web/src/app/%5Blocale%5D/admin/db-actions.ts#L232-L341), [apps/web/Dockerfile:3-10](/Users/hletrd/flash-shared/gallery/apps/web/Dockerfile#L3-L10), [apps/web/scripts/mysql-connection-options.js:11-23](/Users/hletrd/flash-shared/gallery/apps/web/scripts/mysql-connection-options.js#L11-L23)
- Failure scenario: backup and restore spawn `mysqldump` and `mysql` directly, so they only work if the host/container has `mariadb-client` installed and on `PATH`. For non-local DB hosts, the code also forces `--ssl-mode=REQUIRED`, which can fail against private/self-signed deployments unless `DB_SSL=false` is set.
- Fix: keep this path behind the provided Docker image, or add startup checks and clearer admin-facing errors for missing client binaries and TLS incompatibilities. If private MySQL certs are expected, document the `DB_SSL=false` escape hatch prominently and validate it in deployment testing.
- Confidence: medium

